==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} вҖ“ a hand with emphasizing claws or fingernails.

Phonetically borrowed to represent an earthly branch. It also started meaning "ugly" as a simplified form of an unrelated character with same pronunciation, [[йҶң]].

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=дё’,г—ә,р ғ }}

{{zh-ref|Smith (2010)}} proposes that {{lang|zh|дё‘}} graphically depicts the claw-like "final, narrow phase of the moon"; he glosses it as "thing that pinches > pincer" and groups it into a word-family which is based on {{och-l|жүӯ|twist, pinch}} and also includes
* {{och-l|жүӢ|hand}};
* {{och-l|жқ»}} ~ {{och-l|жқҪ|manacle}}, which equally uses {{och-l|дё‘}} or {{och-l|жүӢ}} as phonophoric, as noted by {{zh-ref|Unger (1995)}} and {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}};
* {{och-l|зҙҗ}} ~ {{och-l|йҲ•|grip handle}}, with which ''Shuowen'' glosses {{och-l|дё‘}};
* {{och-l|зӢғ|animal tracks}}, suggested to mean "animals' fingers" by {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}}.

Its association with the ox is from {{der|zh|aav}} ({{zh-ref|Mei, 1980}}; {{zh-ref|Norman, 1985}}; {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 2013}}); compare {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*c-luЛҗ||water buffalo}}, {{cog|mkh-pro|*krpiК” ~ *krpiiw ~ *krpuК” ~ *(kr)puh||buffalo}}, {{cog|aav-pro|*k.r.pu.y||buffalo}}.

